                    <h2><b>Makli</b> & Keenjhar</h2>
                    <p>
                        Starting with an introduction to the Makli graveyard (situated near the city of Thatta), which is one of the largest graveyards in the world and a UNESCO heritage site. The children explore the tombs, understand the history,  and appreciate the efforts involved in maintaining such a significant site. The next stop is at Keenjhar Lake, which is situated along the Indus flyway. The lake is a major source of water for Karachi, and is one of the largest freshwater lakes in Pakistan. Through this eco-tour students gain a better understanding of a significant area surrounding Karachi, one that acts as an essential water source.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The students understand the significance of the lake and how it is a major source of water for Karachi. Gain an understanding of how Keenjhar Lake freshwater wetlands ecosystem is being degraded by increased urban and domestic effluent discharge, and irresponsible tourism. Interact with the local village elders and discuss how they have had to look for alternate sources of income due to the decreasing fish population.
                    </p>
